1️⃣ Enumerable / Array Methods

These are essential for manipulating collections.

| Method                    | What it does                         | Example                                                    |     |                 |
| ------------------------- | ------------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------------- | --- | --------------- |
| `each`                    | Iterates through each element        | `[1,2].each {                                              | n   | puts n }`       |
| `map` / `collect`         | Transforms elements                  | `[1,2].map {                                               | n   | n*2 } => [2,4]` |
| `select` / `filter`       | Picks elements matching a condition  | `[1,2,3].select {                                          | n   | n>1 } => [2,3]` |
| `reject`                  | Opposite of select                   | `[1,2,3].reject {                                          | n   | n>1 } => [1]`   |
| `find` / `detect`         | Returns first matching element       | `[1,2,3].find {                                            | n   | n>1 } => 2`     |
| `reduce` / `inject`       | Accumulates a value                  | `[1,2,3].reduce(:+) => 6`                                  |     |                 |
| `group_by`                | Groups elements into a hash by a key | `[1,2,3,4].group_by(&:even?) => {true:[2,4], false:[1,3]}` |     |                 |
| `partition`               | Splits into two arrays               | `[1,2,3].partition(&:even?) => [[2],[1,3]]`                |     |                 |
| `any?` / `all?` / `none?` | Checks conditions                    | `[1,2].any?(&:even?) => true`                              |     |                 |
| `sort` / `sort_by`        | Sorting arrays                       | `[3,1,2].sort => [1,2,3]`                                  |     |                 |
| `uniq`                    | Removes duplicates                   | `[1,2,2].uniq => [1,2]`                                    |     |                 |
| `flatten`                 | Flattens nested arrays               | `[1,[2,3]].flatten => [1,2,3]`                             |     |                 |
| `compact`                 | Removes nils                         | `[1,nil,2].compact => [1,2]`                               |     |                 |
| `each_with_index`         | Iterates with index                  | `[10,20].each_with_index {                                 | v,i | puts i,v }`     |



2️⃣ Hash Methods

Hashes are everywhere in Ruby. Must-know methods:

| Method                  | What it does                  | Example                           |     |                      |
| ----------------------- | ----------------------------- | --------------------------------- | --- | -------------------- |
| `each`                  | Iterates key & value          | `{a:1}.each {                     | k,v | puts k,v }`          |
| `keys` / `values`       | Extract keys or values        | `{a:1}.keys => [:a]`              |     |                      |
| `fetch`                 | Gets value with error/default | `{a:1}.fetch(:b,0) => 0`          |     |                      |
| `merge`                 | Merge two hashes              | `{a:1}.merge({b:2}) => {a:1,b:2}` |     |                      |
| `delete`                | Deletes key                   | `{a:1}.delete(:a) => 1`           |     |                      |
| `has_key?` / `key?`     | Checks key presence           | `{a:1}.key?(:a) => true`          |     |                      |
| `has_value?` / `value?` | Checks value presence         | `{a:1}.value?(1) => true`         |     |                      |
| `transform_values`      | Change values only            | `{a:1}.transform_values{          | v   | v*2} => {a:2}`       |
| `transform_keys`        | Change keys only              | `{a:1}.transform_keys{            | k   | k.to_s} => {"a"=>1}` |
| `invert`                | Swap key/value                | `{a:1}.invert => {1=>:a}`         |     |                      |
| `group_by` (Enumerable) | Useful when hash is iterable  | same as arrays                    |     |                      |


3️⃣ String Methods

Strings are frequently manipulated.


| Method                        | What it does           | Example                          |
| ----------------------------- | ---------------------- | -------------------------------- |
| `upcase` / `downcase`         | Change case            | `"abc".upcase => "ABC"`          |
| `capitalize`                  | Capitalizes first char | `"hello".capitalize => "Hello"`  |
| `strip` / `lstrip` / `rstrip` | Remove whitespace      | `" hi ".strip => "hi"`           |
| `split`                       | Split string           | `"a,b".split(",") => ["a","b"]`  |
| `gsub` / `sub`                | Replace string         | `"abc".gsub("a","x") => "xbc"`   |
| `include?`                    | Check substring        | `"abc".include?("b") => true`    |
| `start_with?` / `end_with?`   | Check prefix/suffix    | `"abc".start_with?("a") => true` |
| `to_i` / `to_f`               | Convert to number      | `"10".to_i => 10`                |
| `to_sym`                      | Convert to symbol      | `"name".to_sym => :name`         |



4️⃣ Numeric Methods

| Method           | Example                      |
| ---------------- | ---------------------------- |
| `even?` / `odd?` | `2.even? => true`            |
| `next` / `succ`  | `1.next => 2`                |
| `pred`           | `2.pred => 1`                |
| `to_f` / `to_i`  | `2.to_f => 2.0`              |
| `abs`            | Absolute value `-3.abs => 3` |
| `round`          | `2.345.round(1) => 2.3`      |


5️⃣ Kernel / General Methods

| Method                             | Example           |
| ---------------------------------- | ----------------- |
| `puts` / `print` / `p`             | Output            |
| `require` / `require_relative`     | Import files/gems |
| `raise`                            | Throw exception   |
| `sleep`                            | Pause execution   |
| `rand`                             | Random number     |
| `class` / `is_a?` / `instance_of?` | Type checking     |




6️⃣ Control Flow Methods / Idiomatic Ruby


| Method        | Use Case                                  |    |                                       |
| ------------- | ----------------------------------------- | -- | ------------------------------------- |
| `yield`       | Pass control to a block                   |    |                                       |
| `tap`         | Chain operations, returns original object |    |                                       |
| `then`        | Similar to tap, for functional chaining   |    |                                       |
| `Object#send` | Call method dynamically                   |    |                                       |
| `             |                                           | =` | Conditional assignment (common idiom) |
| `&.`          | Safe navigation (avoid nil errors)        |    |                                       |
| `dig`         | Access nested hashes/arrays safely        |    |                                       |




7️⃣ Time / Date Methods


| Method       | Example              |
| ------------ | -------------------- |
| `Time.now`   | Current time         |
| `Time.parse` | Parse string to time |
| `strftime`   | Format time          |
